---

## Package Responsibility

This package owns one concern: deciding whether a job is allowed to enter the
processing pipeline, and which slot it occupies when it does. It has no knowledge of
inference, no knowledge of Hub state, and no knowledge of the Gradio UI. It only
answers the question: "Is there capacity right now for a job of this duration?"

---

## The Semaphore Contract

`AdmissionController` uses two `asyncio.Semaphore` instances. These are not
`threading.Semaphore` — they are async-aware and must be used with `await`. The
`acquire()` method is a coroutine and must be called with `await`. The `release()`
method is synchronous and must be called in a `finally` block at every call site.

There is no built-in timeout on `acquire()`. A job that arrives when all slots are
occupied will await indefinitely. In `app.py`, if you want to reject a request after
a waiting period rather than queue it, wrap the `acquire()` call in
`asyncio.wait_for(admission.acquire(...), timeout=QUEUE_WAIT_TIMEOUT_SECS)` and
catch `asyncio.TimeoutError` to return the "at capacity" message. The timeout value
must be defined in `config.py`.

---

## Slot Classification Logic

The routing decision is binary and based solely on the `duration_secs` argument.
Jobs at or below `SHORT_JOB_THRESHOLD_SECS` go to the short-job semaphore. Jobs above
that threshold go to the primary semaphore. There is no third category. If you find
yourself writing an `elif` or a third slot type, reconsider whether you are solving
a real scheduling problem or creating unnecessary complexity.

The `MAX_AUDIO_DURATION_SECS` check must happen before any semaphore acquisition.
A job that exceeds the cap must be rejected immediately with a `ValueError` containing
the measured duration and the cap value. This gives the user the specific information
they need to trim their file. Do not return a generic "too long" message.

---

## Why These Slot Numbers

The primary slot count of 2 is set by `MAX_PRIMARY_SLOTS` in `config.py`. It was
chosen because a 3-minute audio file processed at 45 seconds per minute of audio takes
roughly 135 seconds of CPU time. Two such jobs running concurrently require ~4.5 CPU-
minutes within a 3-minute wall clock window, which fits within the 2-vCPU free tier
allocation without thrashing. A third concurrent long job would push the system into
memory pressure and cause latency to become unpredictable.

If the team upgrades to a paid tier with more CPU, increase `MAX_PRIMARY_SLOTS` in
`config.py` only — never in this file. This is why constants live in config.

---

## Test Requirements for This Package

The admission controller tests must cover four scenarios. First, a short-duration job
must acquire the short-job slot, not the primary slot. Second, a long-duration job
must acquire a primary slot. Third, a job exceeding `MAX_AUDIO_DURATION_SECS` must
raise `ValueError` before any semaphore is touched. Fourth, when both primary slots
are held, a third long job must wait (or timeout if you implement `asyncio.wait_for`)
— it must not acquire a slot until one is released.

All admission controller tests must run without any mocking because the semaphore is
pure in-memory logic with no external dependencies. Use `pytest-asyncio` for async
test functions. Mark async tests with `@pytest.mark.asyncio`.

---

## Running Tests for This Package Only

```bash
pytest tests/test_admission.py -v
```

Expected: all pass, no network calls, no GPU, no HF_TOKEN. These tests must complete
in under 2 seconds total because they exercise only in-memory semaphore logic.
